<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS BRIEFS: DEVELOPER SEEKS LOAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EVELYN DE WOLFE, From staff reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stalled work on the Compton Lazben Hotel, begun in 1986, may resume shortly 
following a request to Compton's City Council last week for a loan of at least 
$1.5 million to the developer of the long-delayed, $30-million project. 
</P>
<P>
Naftali Deutsch, a principal in several firms building the city-backed hotel 
and convention center, told officials that he cannot complete work because he 
is $3 million short. 
</P>
<P>
City Manager James Goins confirmed his intent to recommend to council members 
that they accept Deutsch's offer to come up with $1.5 million if the city is 
willing to loan him the other $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
The project has been beset by financial problems, labor disputes and work 
stoppages since it began. The original completion date was May, 1988, but city 
officials agreed to adjust the completion date to mid-December. 
</P>
<P>
Loaning more money to Deutsch is only one of several alternatives to get going 
on the project again, Goins said. One could include suing Deutsch and his 
partners for breach of contract and hiring a new contractor to finish the job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
