<TEXT>
<P>
A priest and nine other anti-nuclear activists were arrested at the Nevada Test 
Site in the town of Mercury after conducting religious ceremonies at a former 
chapel on the top-secret nuclear compound. Department of Energy spokesman Jim 
Boyer said 10 demonstrators, including some clergy members, were cited for 
penetrating the testing grounds -- a more serious offense than simple 
trespassing -- and transported to the jail in nearby Beatty. The incident was 
part of an annual Easter demonstration called the Lenten Desert Experience, 
sponsored by the group Nevada Desert Experience, which is opposed to nuclear 
weapons testing and the proliferation of the arms race. Boyer said there was no 
breach of classified security. The test site, about 65 miles northwest of Las 
Vegas, is the center of the nation's nuclear weapons testing program. 
